class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right

def find_highest_common_ancestor(root: TreeNode, p: TreeNode, q: TreeNode) -> TreeNode:
    if not root or root == p or root == q:
        return root

    left = find_highest_common_ancestor(root.left, p, q)
    right = find_highest_common_ancestor(root.right, p, q)

    if left and right:
        return root
    elif left:
        return left
    else:
        return right


The function takes in the root of the binary tree, as well as two nodes `p` and `q` whose highest common ancestor we want to find. We start by checking if the root is `None` or if it is one of the nodes `p` or `q`. If either of these conditions is true, we return the root.

Next, we recursively call the function on the left and right subtrees of the root. If both `left` and `right` are not `None`, it means that `p` and `q` are in different subtrees of the root, so the root is their highest common ancestor. Otherwise, we return either `left` or `right`, depending on which one is not `None`.

The time complexity of this function is O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the binary tree, since we visit each node exactly once. The space complexity is O(h), where h is the height of the binary tree, since the maximum number of recursive calls on the call stack is equal to the height of the tree.

